
For your research paper on "Diabetes Prediction Among Children Using Machine Learning", you should focus on supervised learning models, especially classification models, because your goal is to predict whether a child is likely to develop diabetes (typically a binary outcome: diabetic or non-diabetic).

Hereâ€™s a structured guide to the most important models and why you should learn them:

âœ… Essential ML Models to Learn (for Classification)
1. Logistic Regression
Simple, interpretable baseline model.

Works well with linear relationships.

Good starting point for medical data.

2. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
Non-parametric model.

Works well for small datasets.

Easy to understand and explain.

3. Support Vector Machine (SVM)
Good for high-dimensional spaces.

Effective when classes are clearly separated.

Use kernel trick for non-linear data.

4. Decision Tree
Interpretable and easy to visualize.

Handles both categorical and numerical data.

Can overfit, so combine with ensemble methods.

5. Random Forest
Ensemble of decision trees.

Reduces overfitting and improves accuracy.

Robust and widely used in medical prediction tasks.

6. Gradient Boosting (e.g., XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost)
Powerful and accurate.

Often achieves top performance in classification tasks.

Handles missing data well and supports feature importance analysis.

7. Naive Bayes
Works well with small datasets.

Based on probability and Bayesâ€™ Theorem.

Assumes feature independence (good baseline).

8. Neural Networks (MLP / ANN)
Useful for complex and nonlinear patterns.

Requires more data and tuning.

Can be useful if your dataset is large and you aim for deep learning.

